 as Grace Ogot, David Maillu, Promise Okekwe, and Rebeka Njau. Mwangi examines the novels' self-reflexive fictional strategies and their potential to refigure the dynamics of gender and sexuality in Africa and demote the West as the reference point for cultures of the Global South.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 4aArea Studies : African Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Gender Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary History. 4aLiterature : Literary Theory. 4aPhilosophy : Critical Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / African.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143842697640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438426976423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438426976/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles